<REFENTRY ID="baselib---xmknod-1"> <REFMETA>
<REFENTRYTITLE>__xmknod</REFENTRYTITLE>
<REFMISCINFO>Base Libraries</REFMISCINFO>
</REFMETA>
<REFNAMEDIV>
<REFNAME>__xmknod</REFNAME>
<REFPURPOSE>
__xmknod - make block or character special file
</REFPURPOSE>
</REFNAMEDIV>
<REFSYNOPSISDIV>
<REFSYNOPSISDIVINFO>
<DATE>4 Mar 2001</DATE>
</REFSYNOPSISDIVINFO>
<SYNOPSIS>
int __xmknod(int ver,
            __const char *path,
            __mode_t mode,
            __dev_t *dev);
</SYNOPSIS>
</REFSYNOPSISDIV>
<REFSECT1>
<REFSECT1INFO>
<DATE>16 Feb 2001</DATE>
</REFSECT1INFO>
<TITLE>
ver must be 1 or the behavior is undefined.  __xmknod(1, path, mode, dev)
has the same specification as mknod(path, mode, dev).
Note that the format of dev_t is not the same as the argument that the
kernel syscall uses (TODO: need to document what dev_t is).
</TITLE>
<PARA>
__xmknod is not in the source standard; it is only in the binary standard.
mknod is not in the binary standard; it is only in the source standard.
</PARA>
</REFSECT1>
</REFENTRY>
